Frequently Asked Questions
 Updated: April 14, 2020

Pioneer Valley Regional School District will remain closed until Monday, May 4th, 2020.
https://www.wwlp.com/news/massachusetts/watch-live-governor-baker-to-provide-residents-with-coronavirus-update-wednesday-afternoon/

The information detailed in this document is intended to provide guidance for this period. It is important to note that this is a fluid situation and this document will be regularly updated and modified. It is recommended that you revisit frequently for the latest updates and information. 


Click on the link below for the questions specific to:

Student Learning

Special Education 

Activities, Events, and Athletics

General Questions

COVID-19 Resources and Support

Employment/Human Resources



Frequently Asked Questions
Student Learning




Q.
Are the days during the closure counted as school days?
A.
No. These are non-school days. These days will essentially be considered a school closing period (March 16 -May 4th). There is no expectation of online learning or for the provision of educational services during this period. It is important to note that the school year will not extend beyond the 185th day (June 18, 2020)
Q.
Are there expectations around Distance and Online Learning Expectations for Students or Teachers?
A.
Completing continued learning activities during the period of school closure is strongly encouraged for all students, however assignments are not mandatory, are not considered instruction, and will not be graded. For all students K-12, there will be assignments or additional learning provided by the district and teachers. This is being done in the interest of ensuring a continuation of learning to remain in line with our district core values. Additionally, we are providing digital and remote learning opportunities during this closure intended to keep students connected to learning and skill reinforcement, based on guidance from the Massachusetts Commissioner of Education. 

Credit recovery exceptions for those seniors making up for prior failed courses will be addressed on a case by case basis. School Counselors and Administration will contact those students directly. Any junior, sophomores, and freshmen that need credit recovery will be addressed and adjusted once classes resume. Our goal is to make sure all seniors will be able to graduate this year and all students have the opportunity to make up missed credit. 

All teachers and providers will be contacting their students to ensure a continuation of learning. Teachers will be available to communicate with students and/or families to answer questions, as needed, via email, through Google Classroom, or by phone.

Google Meet has been enabled for all students from grade 3 to 12 for the duration of our time away. With this, teachers can hold video conferences with their students at https://meet.google.com/. Pioneer Students can be invited by email or join by typing in a valid meeting code into https://meet.google.com/. Elementary Students do not have email so they can only go to https://meet.google.com/ and join via a meeting code.

Q.
What resources are available for parents and students to enrich learning during this period of closure? 
A.
We are continuing to compile resources and links for all students and will share that information here.

Students are encouraged to continue to access resources through the PVRSD 
website or their individual school website.

Pioneer Valley Regional District Site: https://pvrsdk12.org

Pioneer Valley Regional School: https://pvrs.pvrsdk12.org/academics/class-assignments

Bernardston Elementary School: https://bes.pvrsdk12.org/learning-at-home 

Warwick Community School: https://wcs.pvrsdk12.org 
WCS Teachers have also established Google Classrooms. Please contact your childs teacher for further information.

Northfield Elementary School: https://nes.pvrsdk12.org/ Go to the SCHOOL CLOSURE LEARNING DOCUMENTS link on the homepage. Additionally, grades 3-6 teachers have set up Google Classrooms for their students to use along with the packets that were provided.

The PVRSD technology department is looking at options to provide computer access for students that do not have access at home.

Given this closure, what happens with the MCAS test for students?
A.
Updated on April 14th
MCAS
DESE previously requested and received a waiver from the federal requirement for annual statewide student assessment. Now, with the state legislation enacted, the MCAS testing requirement is waived for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year.
 
As a result of these federal and state actions and in light of the on-going health crisis, the Commissioner of Education is cancelling this springs regular administration of grade-level MCAS tests for students in grades 3-10. 
 
In addition, the legislation allows the Board of Elementary and Secondary Education, upon the Commissioners recommendation, to modify or waive the requirements of the competency determination for high school graduation in order to address disruptions caused by the outbreak of COVID-19 or the state of emergency. The Commissioner is considering various options, and further guidance will be forthcoming. 

We want to make you aware that this announcement also includes the cancellation of the MCAS Alternate Assessment and therefore, MCAS-Alt portfolios will not be submitted, scored, nor reported this school year.
Q.
Will AP tests still occur later this spring?
A.
Updated on April 8th

Test Dates and Times

These are the dates and times for the AP exams that PVRS students will be taking, listed in chronological order:

AP Calculus AB: Tuesday, May 12 at 2pm

AP English Literature and Composition: Wednesday, May 13 at 2pm

AP U.S. History: Friday, May 15 at 2pm

AP Biology: Monday, May 18 at 2pm

AP Environmental Science: Monday, May 18 at 4pm

AP English Language and Composition: Wednesday, May 20 at 2pm.

Please use this link for further information regarding AP exams in May. 
https://apcoronavirusupdates.collegeboard.org/students



Academic Honesty

There will be several security measures in place to ensure fairness for all test takers. If The College Board catches a student cheating, they will inform all colleges that the student has ever sent PSAT, SAT, or AP scores to. This would also apply if students attempt to send test scores in the future.

Internet Accessibility

If you believe internet accessibility might be an issue for your child, you can contact The College Board directly via this
link: https://collegeboard.tfaforms.net/74 

Please let me know if you need assistance in filling out this form due to accessibility.

Accommodations

Students who have approved accommodations from The College Board will automatically be granted those accommodations the day of the test. If your child has approved accommodations, there is no action you need to take before the test.


Updated on March 23rd. 

The College Board has made the decision to move AP exams into an online format that can be taken at home if necessary this spring. The content and timing of the test will also be reduced to ensure that the test is equitable for those who have lost instructional time due to the current situation. All exams, which are typically 2-3 hours depending on the subject, have been reduced to 45 minutes. As for content, please refer to the link below to see which units will and will not be on the exams for each course. There are also additional details on this page you may find helpful.
https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update

As for scheduling, The College Board should have study materials available for each exam by next Friday, April 3. They also have free remote learning resources that can be accessed via the link above. Each subject will have two options for an exam date/time, which at this time have not yet been scheduled. The schedule should also be available by Friday, April 3.

AP free remote learning resources https://apstudents.collegeboard.org/coronavirus-updates#free-ap-classes

AP Updates for School Closures
Q.
What is going to happen in regards to graduation?

A.
As this situation is ever changing, we will have to wait until May 4th to make decisions based on the directions provided by the state at that time. 
Q.
I am looking for general tips on how to support my child during this closure.
A.
We encourage parents/guardians to talk to their kids about the Coronavirus (COVID-19), the following links offer guidance and calming strategies for anyone to use when they are feeling anxious, worried, or afraid.

Here are some additional resources for the parents/guardians on how to go about that discussion.
A guide on how to talk to children about COVID-19 https://higherlogicdownload.s3.amazonaws.com/NASN/3870c72d-fff9-4ed7-833f-215de278d256/UploadedImages/PDFs/02292020_NASP_NASN_COVID-19_parent_handout.pdf 
A video (3min) explaining COVID-19 to children: https://www.brainpop.com/health/diseasesinjuriesandconditions/coronavirus/
A guide on helping a child cope: https://www.cdc.gov/childrenindisasters/pdf/children-coping-factsheet-508.pdf 
And, also a friendly reminder for our parents/guardians to also take care of yourself too! Don't forget to take a break to unwind, and connect with your support system. 
A guide for adults on coping with a crisis: https://emergency.cdc.gov/coping/pdf/Coping_with_Disaster.pdf
If you need help coping with this crisis please ask for help by talking to your counselor or doctor, or contact the SAMHSA Disaster Distress helpline at 1-800- 985-5990

Frequently Asked Questions
Special Education




Q.
My child is on an IEP or 504 Plan, and I am concerned about the implications of the closure on my childs educational progress. 
A.
Upon the conclusion of the closure, and the re-opening of the district, IEP teams will be available to convene to determine what type of impact the closure had on your childs educational progress, and make individualized team based decisions as needed. 
Q.
My child is on an IEP and receives services only (i.e. speech/Language counseling etc.). Will my child receive these services during the closure?
A.
Services will not be provided during the closure, consistent with how this is handled on snow days.
Q.
Will my childs special education liaison, related service provider, and Director of Special Education be available if I have a question during this closure?
A.
Yes, special education teachers, related services providers, and the Director of Special Education will be available to assist with specific questions as needed. You can expect a check in from your childs liaison, in the form of a phone call or email during this time as well. 
Q.
I have made a request for an Initial Evaluation on or after March 16th. What should I expect?
A.
Any timelines associated with an initial evaluation request received on March 16th or during the closure, will be processed using day one of the timeline as the date the district re-opens. For example, if the district re-opens on April 7th, that would count as day one associated with the timeline for an initial evaluation request. In addition, any evaluations that were already in progress, will be given priority and finished as soon as possible when school is back in session.
 Return to FAQs Menu










Frequently Asked Questions
Activities, Events, and Athletics




Q.
Are there any athletic, club, or activity events happening during this period of closure?
A.
No. All school-related events are canceled during this period. 
Q.
Are Spring Sports delayed?
A.
March 26, 2020 Update:

In light of Governor Bakers March 25, 2020 mandate that all schools remain closed until May 4th, the status of spring sports will be addressed by the Board of Directors on a March 30th conference call and an immediate update will be provided to the membership. 

Among TMC recommendations to the Board is that if there is a spring season start date of after April 27th, there will not be an MIAA tournament. This recommendation, as well as a plan to save a spring season for MIAA student-athletes will be the substance of a March 30th Board meeting.

This recent news from the Governor is surreal. The MIAA will continue to monitor this fluid situation and provide updates regarding spring sports as soon as they are made available. Thank you all for your flexibility, understanding and patience. Support and guidance to our schools, student-athletes and to you, our membership, is priority during this uncertain time. 

 Return to FAQs Menu
















Frequently Asked Questions
General Questions




Q.
How will the days of the closure count against school days?
A.
Pioneer Valley Regional School District will be in school through June 18, 2020 which is our regularly scheduled 185th day.
Q.
Currently the schools are closed through April 6, 2020. Will this be extended? How will we be notified?
A.
Pioneer Valley Regional School District will continue to monitor this fluid situation and will make the best determinations in the best interest of the students and staff. Information will continue to be provided via Blackboard Connect, on our PVRSD website, through email, and on all major news outlets.
Q.
What will happen to April vacation (April 20-24)?
A.
Pioneer Valley Regional School District will be closed until May 4th 2020.
Q.
Will there be access to any school buildings during the March 16 - April 6, 2020 closure?
A.
At this time all buildings are closed. All school playgrounds and athletic fields are also closed.
Q.
Will food services be available for students that qualify for free and reduced lunch?
A.
Pioneer Valley Regional School District will be providing breakfast and lunch Grab and Go style daily between 11:15am to 12:00pm. Please see our Meal Service Plan here: Closure Meal Service Plan. Please contact Mike Onorato at onoratom@pvrsdk12.org with questions.
Q.
Will elementary Parent-Teacher Conferences that were scheduled for March/April still be held?
A.
UPDATED 3.25.20 Parent-teacher conferences will not be held as previously scheduled. Teachers and service providers are not able to access the buildings to get the materials needed to prepare for conferences. However, if you have any specific concerns about your childs progress, you may contact his/her teacher.

COVID-19 Resources and Support




Q.
How do I protect my family?
A.
Massachusetts currently has emergency measures, such as school closings and limits on public gatherings, in place to help stop this virus from spreading. The best prevention methods for yourself and your family are the same as with other respiratory viruses: 1) avoid close contact with others (social distancing) 2) wash your hands (preferred) or use alcohol based hand sanitizer 3) cover your cough or sneeze, use a tissue, not your hands, and dispose of it quickly 4) clean commonly used touch points regularly (doorknobs, countertops, faucet handles) 5) avoid touching your hands to your face 6) stay home/away from others if you are sick.
If you or a family member have signs of illness such as fever, shortness of breath or a cough, call your healthcare provider. Do NOT show up to your doctors office unannounced, call the office first to discuss symptoms and a nurse or other practitioner will do phone triage and consult if further action is needed. Most offices do not currently have the capability to do COVID-19 testing, most of the testing is being done on patients who are ill enough to require hospital level care. If you have an emergency, call 911.
Resources:
Symptoms: COVID-19 vs. cold, flu, allergies
CDC: How to prepare
CDC: Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) and children
Q.
What does social distancing mean?
A.
The single most important factor during a viral outbreak is to stop the spread of the germs that cause the disease. Coronavirus (COVID-19) is thought to spread between people (within about 6ft) via tiny respiratory droplets (such as from a cough or sneeze). The term social distancing refers to preventing the spread of germs between people by physically distancing ourselves from each other. In this instance, the public refers to outside of your home. This concept is best explained in a recently published article in response to Coronavirus (COVID-19) and best practice for prevention of disease transmission: "Social Distancing: This is Not a Snow Day".
In our social world, the idea of isolating ourselves feels contradictory. The good news is that we have many ways to connect with each other virtually. Now is the time to explore ways to be social without being face to face. There is an extreme focus on protecting our physical health during this outbreak, but it is also important to be mindful of the negative effects that social isolation can have on our emotional and mental health. Try to keep up with a healthy diet, remember to hydrate and stay active, going for a hike, bike or walk can do your body a world of good.
Q.
Where can I get more information on COVID-19?
A.
The Massachusetts Department of Public Health (MDPH) has a site dedicated to daily updates on the Coronavirus outbreak, their web page also has a link to the Center of 
Disease Controls site. Here are a few resources for talking with children about Coronavirus. This will be a challenging time for all of us, keeping yourself informed and knowing how to protect yourself and your family will give you the confidence to weather this storm. 
Talking with elementary school kids about coronavirus
Talking with middle/high school kids about coronavirus

As this public health crisis continues, the amount of information and news surrounding this topic is increasing dramatically. During this time, false information and misleading claims and advice are rampant. Take the time to look at the sources of what you are hearing and/or reading. If the study you are reading about is not scientific (following guidelines for scientific research) or it is produced by a company making a claim for a cure and selling a product, the information may not be reliable. Reliable sources of information come from organizations such as the Center for Disease Control (CDC), Department of Public Health (DPH/MDPH) and the World Health Organization (WHO).

This pandemic is an unprecedented time in modern history. We are already seeing the implications of this crisis on the larger scale, such as school closures and a statewide ban on non-essential travel. The smaller implications of these circumstances are only beginning to be realized. Impacts on our homes, finances, jobs, personal relationships will undoubtedly continue for an unknown amount of time. We at PVRSD are committed to offering resources and support during your time of need. Our district is known for supporting our families and staff, we will get through this together. Please scroll through the following resources and reach out to us as needed for guidance and support.
